ich should keep the cluster stable since the replicas can handle individual node downtime.\n\nThe key insight is that I need both the old and new nodes to have allocation attributes—just with different values—so I can then configure the app-data index to route its shards to the new nodes. My implementation plan is to first update the existing nodes with `node.attr.zone: original`, restart them, then create the new data-only nodes with `node.attr.zone: new`, and finally set up index routing to move the shards over.\n\nFor the new data nodes, I'm realizing they don't actually need their own headless service since they're data-only and won't be master-eligible—they'll just connect to the existing master nodes through discovery. However, I should verify whether they need DNS resolution for inter-node communication during shard recovery. their IP addresses directly, so I don't strictly need a headless service for the new data nodes, but it's good practice to create one for DNS naming.\n\nNow I'm setting up the implementation plan: first I'll update the existing ConfigMap to add a zone attribute marking the original nodes, then do a rolling restart of the current StatefulSet, and finally create a new ConfigMap for the data-only nodes.\n\nWriting configuration files... Finishing the routing update to move shards to the new zone, then I need to ensure the new data nodes have the same transport SSL certificates as the existing cluster so they can communicate securely.\n\nSince the verification mode only checks that certificates are signed by the trusted CA rather than validating hostnames, the new nodes can reuse the same `es-http-tls` secret. I should also check what file-realm secret is being used for authentication.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":532,"cache_read_input_tokens":34888,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":532},"output_t